{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_2776e44adffeWi2i79hWf80hqu","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d8891bbde001iqTWRo4U8NduE1","parts":[{"id":"prt_d8891cd79001MDHZ7p9ZziwMx8","messageID":"msg_d8891bbde001iqTWRo4U8NduE1","sessionID":"ses_2776e44adffeWi2i79hWf80hqu","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_6015bfcd1efa4fdf8bb98807","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/README.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: Robot Framework\n2: ===============\n3: \n4: .. contents::\n5:    :local:\n6: \n7: Introduction\n8: ------------\n9: \n10: `Robot Framework <http://robotframework.org>`_ |r| is a generic open source\n11: automation framework for acceptance testing, acceptance test driven\n12: development (ATDD), and robotic process automation (RPA). It has simple plain\n13: text syntax and it can be extended easily with generic and custom libraries.\n14: \n15: Robot Framework is operating system and application independent. It is\n16: implemented using `Python <http://python.org>`_ which is also the primary\n17: language to extend it. The framework has a rich ecosystem around it consisting\n18: of various generic libraries and tools that are developed as separate projects.\n19: For more information about Robot Framework and the ecosystem, see\n20: http://robotframework.org.\n21: \n22: Robot Framework project is hosted on GitHub_ where you can find source code,\n23: an issue tracker, and some further documentation. Downloads are hosted on PyPI_.\n24: \n25: Robot Framework development is sponsored by non-profit `Robot Framework Foundation\n26: <http://robotframework.org/foundation>`_. If you are using the framework\n27: and benefiting from it, consider joining the foundation to help maintaining\n28: the framework and developing it further.\n29: \n30: .. _GitHub: https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework\n31: .. _PyPI: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/robotframework\n32: \n33: .. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/robotframework.svg?label=version\n34:    :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/robotframework\n35:    :alt: Latest version\n36: \n37: .. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/robotframework.svg\n38:    :target: http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.html\n39:    :alt: License\n40: \n41: Installation\n42: ------------\n43: \n44: If you already have Python_ with `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_ installed,\n45: you can simply run::\n46: \n47:     pip install robotframework\n48: \n49: For more detailed installation instructions, including installing Python, see\n50: `<INSTALL.rst>`__.\n51: \n52: Robot Framework requires Python 3.8 or newer and runs also on `PyPy <http://pypy.org>`_.\n53: The latest version that supports Python 3.6 and 3.7 is `Robot Framework 6.1.1`__.\n54: If you need to use Python 2, `Jython <http://jython.org>`_ or\n55: `IronPython <http://ironpython.net>`_, you can use `Robot Framework 4.1.3`__.\n56: \n57: __ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/tree/v6.1.1#readme\n58: __ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/tree/v4.1.3#readme\n59: \n60: Example\n61: -------\n62: \n63: Below is a simple example test case for testing login to some system.\n64: You can find more examples with links to related demo projects from\n65: http://robotframework.org.\n66: \n67: .. code:: robotframework\n68: \n69:     *** Settings ***\n70:     Documentation     A test suite with a single test for valid login.\n71:     ...\n72:     ...               This test has a workflow that is created using keywords in\n73:     ...               the imported resource file.\n74:     Resource          login.resource\n75: \n76:     *** Test Cases ***\n77:     Valid Login\n78:         Open Browser To Login Page\n79:         Input Username    demo\n80:         Input Password    mode\n81:         Submit Credentials\n82:         Welcome Page Should Be Open\n83:         [Teardown]    Close Browser\n84: \n85: Usage\n86: -----\n87: \n88: Tests (or tasks) are executed from the command line using the ``robot``\n89: command or by executing the ``robot`` module directly like ``python -m robot`` .\n90: \n91: The basic usage is giving a path to a test (or task) file or directory as an\n92: argument with possible command line options before the path::\n93: \n94:     robot tests.robot\n95:     robot --variable BROWSER:Firefox --outputdir results path/to/tests/\n96: \n97: Additionally, there is the ``rebot`` tool for combining results and otherwise\n98: post-processing outputs::\n99: \n100:     rebot --name Example output1.xml output2.xml\n101: \n102: Run ``robot --help`` and ``rebot --help`` for more information about the command\n103: line usage. For a complete reference manual see `Robot Framework User Guide`_.\n104: \n105: Documentation\n106: -------------\n107: \n108: - `Robot Framework User Guide\n109:   <http://robotframework.org/robotframework/#user-guide>`_\n110: - `Standard libraries\n111:   <http://robotframework.org/robotframework/#standard-libraries>`_\n112: - `API documentation <http://robot-framework.readthedocs.org>`_\n113: - `General documentation <http://robotframework.org/>`_\n114: \n115: Support and Contact\n116: -------------------\n117: \n118: - `Slack <http://slack.robotframework.org/>`_\n119: - `Forum <https://forum.robotframework.org/>`_\n120: - `robotframework-users\n121:   <https://groups.google.com/group/robotframework-users/>`_ mailing list\n122: \n123: Contributing\n124: ------------\n125: \n126: Interested to contribute to Robot Framework? Great! In that case it is a good\n127: start by looking at the `<CONTRIBUTING.rst>`__. If you\n128: do not already have an issue you would like to work on, you can check\n129: issues with `good new issue`__ and `help wanted`__ labels.\n130: \n131: Remember also that there are many other tools and libraries in the wider\n132: `Robot Framework ecosystem <http://robotframework.org>`_ that you can\n133: contribute to!\n134: \n135: __ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3A%22good+first+issue%22\n136: __ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3A%22help+wanted%22\n137: \n138: License and Trademark\n139: ---------------------\n140: \n141: Robot Framework is open source software provided under the `Apache License 2.0`__.\n142: Robot Framework documentation and other similar content use the\n143: `Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Unported`__ license. Most libraries and tools\n144: in the ecosystem are also open source, but they may use different licenses.\n145: \n146: Robot Framework trademark is owned by `Robot Framework Foundation`_.\n147: \n148: __ http://apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n149: __ http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0\n150: \n151: .. |r| unicode:: U+00AE\n\n(End of file - total 151 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"Robot Framework\n===============\n\n.. contents::\n   :local:\n\nIntroduction\n------------\n\n`Robot Framework <http://robotframework.org>`_ |r| is a generic open source\nautomation framework for acceptance testing, acceptance test driven\ndevelopment (ATDD), and robotic process automation (RPA). It has simple plain\ntext syntax and it can be extended easily with generic and custom libraries.\n\nRobot Framework is operating system and application independent. It is\nimplemented using `Python <http://python.org>`_ which is also the primary\nlanguage to extend it. The framework has a rich ecosystem around it consisting\nof various generic libraries and tools that are developed as separate projects.\nFor more information about Robot Framework and the ecosystem, see\nhttp://robotframework.org.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.rst","time":{"start":1776112750368,"end":1776112750379}}}]}
