{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_2776e44adffeWi2i79hWf80hqu","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d8891d360001mbDFmghpc2sM6s","parts":[{"id":"prt_d8891e1f80014F84sa4HUBsw5D","messageID":"msg_d8891d360001mbDFmghpc2sM6s","sessionID":"ses_2776e44adffeWi2i79hWf80hqu","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_01359d92c57049b0b6533958","state":{"status":"pending","input":{},"raw":""}}]}
{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_2776e44adffeWi2i79hWf80hqu","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d8891d360001mbDFmghpc2sM6s","parts":[{"id":"prt_d8891e045001DueJk5V2ftd7nM","messageID":"msg_d8891d360001mbDFmghpc2sM6s","sessionID":"ses_2776e44adffeWi2i79hWf80hqu","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_d5bcffbc91164452a53b0b03","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/INSTALL.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/INSTALL.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: Installation instructions\n2: =========================\n3: \n4: These instructions cover installing `Robot Framework <https://robotframework.org>`_\n5: and its preconditions on different operating systems. If you already have\n6: `Python <http://python.org>`_ installed, you can install Robot Framework using\n7: the standard package manager `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_::\n8: \n9:     pip install robotframework\n10: \n11: .. contents::\n12:    :depth: 2\n13:    :local:\n14: \n15: .. START USER GUIDE IGNORE\n16: .. Installation instructions are included also in the User Guide.\n17: .. Following content is excluded when the UG is built.\n18: .. default-role:: code\n19: .. role:: file(emphasis)\n20: .. role:: option(code)\n21: .. END USER GUIDE IGNORE\n22: \n23: Python installation\n24: -------------------\n25: \n26: `Robot Framework`_ is implemented using Python_, and a precondition to install it\n27: is having Python or its alternative implementation `PyPy <https://pypy.org>`_\n28: installed. Another recommended precondition is having the pip_ package manager\n29: available.\n30: \n31: Robot Framework requires Python 3.8 or newer. The latest version that supports\n32: Python 3.6 and 3.7 is `Robot Framework 6.1.1`__. If you need to use Python 2,\n33: `Jython <http://jython.org>`_ or `IronPython <http://ironpython.net>`_,\n34: you can use `Robot Framework 4.1.3`__.\n35: \n36: __ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/blob/v6.1.1/INSTALL.rst\n37: __ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/blob/v4.1.3/INSTALL.rst\n38: \n39: Installing Python on Linux\n40: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n41: \n42: On Linux you should have suitable Python installation with pip_ available\n43: by default. If not, you need to consult your distributions documentation\n44: to learn how to install them. This is also true if you want to use some other\n45: Python version than the one provided by your distribution by default.\n46: \n47: To check what Python version you have installed, you can run `python --version`\n48: command in a terminal:\n49: \n50: .. code:: bash\n51: \n52:   $ python --version\n53:   Python 3.10.13\n54: \n55: Notice that if your distribution provides also older Python 2, running `python`\n56: may use that. To use Python 3, you can use `python3` command or even more version\n57: specific command like `python3.8`. You need to use these version specific variants\n58: also if you have multiple Python 3 versions installed and need to pinpoint which\n59: one to use:\n60: \n61: .. code:: bash\n62: \n63:   $ python3.11 --version\n64:   Python 3.11.7\n65:   $ python3.12 --version\n66:   Python 3.12.1\n67: \n68: Installing Robot Framework directly under the system provided Python\n69: has a risk that possible problems can affect the whole Python installation\n70: used also by the operating system itself. Nowadays\n71: Linux distributions typically use `user installs`__ by default to avoid such\n72: problems, but users can also themselves decide to use `virtual environments`_.\n73: \n74: __ https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/user_guide/#user-installs\n75: \n76: Installing Python on Windows\n77: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n78: \n79: On Windows Python is not available by default, but it is easy to install.\n80: The recommended way to install it is using the official Windows installers available\n81: at http://python.org. For other alternatives, such as installing from the\n82: Microsoft Store, see the `official Python documentation`__.\n83: \n84: When installing Python on Windows, it is recommended to add Python to PATH_\n85: to make it and tools like pip and Robot Framework easier to execute from\n86: the command line. When using the `official installer`__, you just need\n87: to select the `Add Python 3.x to PATH` checkbox on the first dialog.\n88: \n89: To make sure Python installation has been successful and Python has been\n90: added to `PATH`, you can open the command prompt and execute `python --version`:\n91: \n92: .. code:: batch\n93: \n94:   C:\\>python --version\n95:   Python 3.10.9\n96: \n97: If you install multiple Python versions on Windows, the version that is used\n98: when you execute `python` is the one first in `PATH`. If you need to use others,\n99: the easiest way is using the `py launcher`__:\n100: \n101: .. code:: batch\n102: \n103:   C:\\>py --version\n104:   Python 3.10.9\n105:   C:\\>py -3.12 --version\n106:   Python 3.12.1\n107: \n108: __ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html\n109: __ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#windows-full\n110: __ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#launcher\n111: \n112: Installing Python on macOS\n113: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n114: \n115: MacOS does not provide Python 3 compatible Python version by default, so it\n116: needs to be installed separately. The recommended  approach is using the official\n117: macOS installers available at http://python.org. If you are using a package\n118: manager like `Homebrew <https://brew.sh/>`_, installing Python via it is\n119: possible as well.\n120: \n121: You can validate Python installation on macOS using `python --version` like on\n122: other operating systems.\n123: \n124: PyPy installation\n125: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n126: \n127: PyPy_ is an alternative Python implementation. Its main advantage over the\n128: standard Python implementation is that it can be faster and use less memory,\n129: but this depends on the context where and how it is used. If execution speed\n130: is important, at least testing PyPy is probably a good idea.\n131: \n132: Installing PyPy is a straightforward procedure and you can find both installers\n133: and installation instructions at http://pypy.org. To validate that PyPy installation\n134: was successful, run `pypy --version` or `pypy3 --version`.\n135: \n136: .. note:: Using Robot Framework with PyPy is officially supported only on Linux.\n137: \n138: Configuring `PATH`\n139: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n140: \n141: The `PATH environment variable`__ lists directories where commands executed in\n142: a system are searched from. To make using Python, pip_ and Robot Framework easier\n143: from the command line, it is recommended to add the Python installation directory\n144: as well as the directory where commands like `pip` and `robot` are installed\n145: into `PATH`.\n146: \n147: __ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PATH_(variable)\n148: \n149: When using Python on Linux or macOS, Python and tools installed with it should be\n150: automatically in `PATH`. If you nevertheless need to update `PATH`, you\n151: typically need to edit some system wide or user specific configuration file.\n152: Which file to edit and how depends on the operating system and you need to\n153: consult its documentation for more details.\n154: \n155: On Windows the easiest way to make sure `PATH` is configured correctly is\n156: setting the `Add Python 3.x to PATH` checkbox when `running the installer`__.\n157: To manually modify `PATH` on Windows, follow these steps:\n158: \n159: 1. Find `Environment Variables` under `Settings`. There are variables affecting\n160:    the whole system and variables affecting only the current user. Modifying\n161:    the former will require admin rights, but modifying the latter is typically\n162:    enough.\n163: \n164: 2. Select `PATH` (often written like `Path`) and click `Edit`. If you are\n165:    editing user variables and `PATH` does not exist, click `New` instead.\n166: \n167: 3. Add both the Python installation directory and the :file:`Scripts` directory\n168:    under the installation directory into `PATH`.\n169: \n170: 4. Exit the dialog with `Ok` to save the changes.\n171: \n172: 5. Start a new command prompt for the changes to take effect.\n173: \n174: __ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#the-full-installer\n175: \n176: Installing using pip\n177: --------------------\n178: \n179: These instructions cover installing Robot Framework using pip_, the standard\n180: Python package manager. If you are using some other package manager like\n181: `Conda <https://conda.io>`_, you can use it instead but need to study its\n182: documentation for instructions.\n183: \n184: When installing Python, you typically get pip installed automatically. If\n185: that is not the case, you need to check the documentation of that Python\n186: installation for instructions how to install it separately.\n187: \n188: Running `pip` command\n189: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n190: \n191: Typically you use pip by running the `pip` command, but on Linux you may need\n192: to use `pip3` or even more Python version specific variant like `pip3.8`\n193: instead. When running `pip` or any of its variants, the pip version that is\n194: found first in PATH_ will be used. If you have multiple Python versions\n195: installed, you may need to pinpoint which exact version you want to use.\n196: This is typically easiest done by running `python -m pip` and substituting\n197: `python` with the Python version you want to use.\n198: \n199: To make sure you have pip available, you can run `pip --version` or equivalent.\n200: \n201: Examples on Linux:\n202: \n203: .. code:: bash\n204: \n205:   $ pip --version\n206:   pip 23.2.1 from ... (python 3.10)\n207:   $ python3.12 -m pip --version\n208:   pip 23.3.1 from ... (python 3.12)\n209: \n210: Examples on Windows:\n211: \n212: .. code:: batch\n213: \n214:   C:\\> pip --version\n215:   pip 23.2.1 from ... (python 3.10)\n216:   C:\\> py -m 3.12 -m pip --version\n217:   pip 23.3.2 from ... (python 3.12)\n218: \n219: In the subsequent sections pip is always run using the `pip` command. You may\n220: need to use some of the other approaches explained above in your environment.\n221: \n222: Installing and uninstalling Robot Framework\n223: ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n224: \n225: The easiest way to use pip is by letting it find and download packages it\n226: installs from the `Python Package Index (PyPI)`__, but it can also install\n227: packages downloaded from the PyPI separately. The most common usages are\n228: shown below and pip_ documentation has more information and examples.\n229: \n230: __ PyPI_\n231: \n232: .. code:: bash\n233: \n234:     # Install the latest version (does not upgrade)\n235:     pip install robotframework\n236: \n237:     # Upgrade to the latest stable version\n238:     pip install --upgrade robotframework\n239: \n240:     # Upgrade to the latest version even if it is a pre-release\n241:     pip install --upgrade --pre robotframework\n242: \n243:     # Install a specific version\n244:     pip install robotframework==7.0\n245: \n246:     # Install separately downloaded package (no network connection needed)\n247:     pip install robotframework-7.0-py3-none-any.whl\n248: \n249:     # Install latest (possibly unreleased) code directly from GitHub\n250:     pip install https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/archive/master.zip\n251: \n252:     # Uninstall\n253:     pip uninstall robotframework\n254: \n255: Installing from source\n256: ----------------------\n257: \n258: Another installation alternative is getting Robot Framework source code\n259: and installing it using the provided `setup.py` script. This approach is\n260: recommended only if you do not have pip_ available for some reason.\n261: \n262: You can get the source code by downloading a source distribution package\n263: from PyPI_ and extracting it. An alternative is cloning the GitHub_\n264: repository and checking out the needed release tag.\n265: \n266: Once you have the source code, you can install it with the following command:\n267: \n268: .. code:: bash\n269: \n270:    python setup.py install\n271: \n272: The `setup.py` script accepts several arguments allowing, for example,\n273: installation into a non-default location that does not require administrative\n274: rights. It is also used for creating different distribution packages. Run\n275: `python setup.py --help` for more details.\n276: \n277: Verifying installation\n278: ----------------------\n279: \n280: To make sure that the correct Robot Framework version has been installed, run\n281: the following command:\n282: \n283: .. code:: bash\n284: \n285:    $ robot --version\n286:    Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.10.3 on linux)\n287: \n288: If running these commands fails with a message saying that the command is\n289: not found or recognized, a good first step is double-checking the PATH_\n290: configuration.\n291: \n292: If you have installed Robot Framework under multiple Python versions,\n293: running `robot` will execute the one first in PATH_. To select explicitly,\n294: you can run `python -m robot` and substitute `python` with the right Python\n295: version.\n296: \n297: .. code:: bash\n298: \n299:    $ python3.12 -m robot --version\n300:    Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.12.1 on linux)\n301: \n302:    C:\\>py -3.11 -m robot --version\n303:    Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.11.7 on win32)\n304: \n305: Dependencies\n306: ------------\n307: \n308: Robot Framework core functionality has no mandatory dependencies other than\n309: Python and its standard library. Some individual features may require optional\n310: dependencies to be installed, though. What dependencies are needed is always\n311: explained in the relevant documentation.\n312: \n313: Virtual environments\n314: --------------------\n315: \n316: Python `virtual environments`__ allow Python packages to be installed in\n317: an isolated location for a particular system or application, rather than\n318: installing all packages into the same global location. They have\n319: two main use cases:\n320: \n321: - Install packages needed by different projects into their own environments.\n322:   This avoids conflicts if projects need different versions of same packages.\n323: \n324: - Avoid installing everything under the global Python installation. This is\n325:   especially important on Linux where the global Python installation may be\n326:   used by the distribution itself and messing it up can cause severe problems.\n327: \n328: __ https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/guides/installing-using-pip-and-virtual-environments/#creating-a-virtual-environment\n329: \n330: .. _PATH: `Configuring path`_\n331: .. _PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/robotframework\n332: .. _GitHub: https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework\n\n(End of file - total 332 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"Installation instructions\n=========================\n\nThese instructions cover installing `Robot Framework <https://robotframework.org>`_\nand its preconditions on different operating systems. If you already have\n`Python <http://python.org>`_ installed, you can install Robot Framework using\nthe standard package manager `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_::\n\n    pip install robotframework\n\n.. contents::\n   :depth: 2\n   :local:\n\n.. START USER GUIDE IGNORE\n.. Installation instructions are included also in the User Guide.\n.. Following content is excluded when the UG is built.\n.. default-role:: code\n.. role:: file(emphasis)\n.. role:: option(code)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"INSTALL.rst","time":{"start":1776112755189,"end":1776112755194}}}]}
